WEBVTT



00:00:20.768 --> 00:00:22.560
Well, this is the last week of this study.

00:00:22.496 --> 00:00:32.544
And if you're like most groups, you've decided that you're going to spend the next year or two together, which means that tonight you're going to sign the group agreement. Very simply, the group agreement is a mechanism for aligning the exit

00:00:32.064 --> 00:00:34.752
The expectations of everybody in your group.

00:00:34.592 --> 00:00:41.984
We've seen, over time, that groups who leverage the agreement at this point and sign it end up having a better experience over long term.

00:00:41.568 --> 00:00:46.080
Now some of you might be thinking I'm not so sure that I want to sign anything.

00:00:45.728 --> 00:00:55.776
Well, this isn't like signing a mortgage or a car loan or even submitting your tax return. It's just a simple way of indicating that you understand how this group is going to operate and that you

00:00:55.296 --> 00:00:56.544
And that you agree.

00:00:56.384 --> 00:01:03.616
So tonight your leader is going to walk you through line by line giving you the chance to offer your input, ask questions, and clarify things before you sign them.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:12.864
And before your leader does that, I want to take just a few minutes and highlight a couple of aspects of the agreement itself. Let's start with the purpose statement, specifically the first half.

00:01:12.512 --> 00:01:15.008
To provide a predictable environment.

00:01:14.784 --> 00:01:24.832
Now, predictable in this statement doesn't mean boring or stale or rote. Predictable means that you know who's going to be there from week to week. You know where you're going to meet, you know what time,

00:01:24.352 --> 00:01:34.400
You know what the format of the meeting is going to be. You even know how long the group is planning to stay together. Predictability is a big deal and people feeling comfortable enough to open up and talk about it.

00:01:33.920 --> 00:01:35.584
And talk about what's really going on.

00:01:35.456 --> 00:01:40.736
Now the second part where participants pursue healthy relationships and spiritual growth.

00:01:40.384 --> 00:01:46.112
Pursue is the operative word there because we can't guarantee healthy relationships.

00:01:45.824 --> 00:01:47.904
And we can't guarantee spiritual growth.

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:49.376
Your leader can't...

00:01:49.152 --> 00:01:56.032
The church can't. It's something that has to happen by a combined effort of everybody in the group. And it really is dependent on you.

00:01:55.616 --> 00:01:59.040
So this group is where you have the opportunity.

00:01:58.848 --> 00:02:02.528
To pursue these healthy relationships and spiritual growth.

00:02:02.784 --> 00:02:09.248
Next, let's turn our attention to the values and goals section and take a look at multiplication. It's the last value, although it's a really important one.

00:02:09.472 --> 00:02:13.120
Now multiplication is the idea that when this group comes to an end

00:02:13.056 --> 00:02:17.216
Two groups, or maybe even three groups, will be born out of this one group.

00:02:17.056 --> 00:02:19.136
Now you may be thinking, "Wait a minute.

00:02:18.944 --> 00:02:23.232
Why are we talking about a group ending before the group has really even gotten started?

00:02:23.264 --> 00:02:32.448
Well, it's because in all things, there's a beginning and there's an end, and groups are no exception. The best groups know that there's going to be an end, and they plan for it.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:37.792
Also, one of the three vital relationships as we talked about is influence with outsiders.

00:02:37.472 --> 00:02:47.520
And the way we keep groups from being too internally focused is remembering that there's other people out there who also need a space in these circles. That's why we keep our groups focused.

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:49.920
Groups focused on it and value multiplication.

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:55.520
And finally, let's look at the group guidelines. Specifically, the idea that this is going to be a closed group.

00:02:55.488 --> 00:03:02.464
Now, "closed" doesn't mean "closed down" or "closed minded." It just means "closed to new people without the consent of everybody in the group."

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:12.288
We want there to be a predictability, remember, from the purpose statement. We want to make sure that the people around the circle stay consistent from week to week. Because if you think about it, it's really challenging something

00:03:11.808 --> 00:03:21.856
sometimes to open up and share who you really are, especially if you don't know who's going to be there from week to week. And the reality is that if you're introducing new people from week to week, some

00:03:21.376 --> 00:03:25.792
Some folks just aren't going to share, which thwarts the overall purpose of the group.

00:03:25.728 --> 00:03:30.240
That's why we don't add new people unless everybody agrees together.

00:03:30.048 --> 00:03:35.136
So your leader is going to walk you through line by line and make sure you understand the group agreement and are able to sign it.

00:03:35.072 --> 00:03:40.128
But first, Andy Stanley is going to give us one more idea about the benefit of living in community.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:06.048
or not, here you are on week 8. Over the past couple of months, you've explored how intimacy with God, community with insiders, and influence with outsiders are essential ingredients for spiritual growth.

00:04:05.568 --> 00:04:12.864
For spiritual growth and you've taken some time to share your stories with one another and now you know each other better than you ever imagined was possible

00:04:12.608 --> 00:04:19.776
I hope this has helped you take first steps in creating life-changing community together. As you move forward, your goal should be to keep showing up.

00:04:19.584 --> 00:04:22.144
Joining in and keep being real.

00:04:22.688 --> 00:04:28.800
Now as the study comes to a close, I want to talk to you for just a few minutes about one more benefit of living.

00:04:28.608 --> 00:04:38.656
and community. It's an incredibly practical benefit that has the potential to create a powerful connection between your faith and the circumstances of your everyday life. Now, the most simple

00:04:38.176 --> 00:04:48.224
The most difficult phone calls that we get at church are from people who are in crisis. We hear things like, "I need someone to help me with my 16-year-old," they say, "or my marriage is crumbling." And the first question we

00:04:47.744 --> 00:04:56.480
The question we ask is, are you in a group? And here's why. When people are in a community group, we know there is someone there to help them when they stumble.

00:04:56.256 --> 00:05:06.304
I wish that everyone could experience this sort of structured community with other Christians doing life together that you have now committed to. In Luke's Gospel, Jesus says this:

00:05:05.824 --> 00:05:15.872
Things that cause people to stumble are bound to come. In other words, hardship and challenges are inevitable in life. There are times when we're going to be stretched to our limits.

00:05:15.392 --> 00:05:25.440
It's absolutely unavoidable. It doesn't matter how smart you are, how mature you are, or how much Bible you know, it's just going to happen. You can't get through life without stumbling,

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:33.472
from time to time. But here's the thing: while it's easy to stumble out of faith or away from what you believe, it's almost impossible to stumble

00:05:33.184 --> 00:05:43.232
out of community because community is relational, is tangible. In community, people are paying attention to what's going on in your life. They provide help and perspective.

00:05:42.752 --> 00:05:45.216
When life feels a bit upside down.

00:05:45.056 --> 00:05:55.104
King Solomon, who with the exception of Jesus was the wisest man who ever lived, said this in the book of Ecclesiastes. Listen to this. Two are better than one because they have a good

00:05:54.624 --> 00:06:00.096
Have a good return for their labor. If they fall down, they can help each other get back up.

00:05:59.776 --> 00:06:09.824
But pity those who fall and have no one to help them up. When people in community fall, they have someone to help them get back on their feet. People in community are the hand

00:06:09.344 --> 00:06:19.392
the hands and feet of Jesus for the other people in the group. When times are tough, that kind of support can actually be the difference between becoming angry with God and experiencing the love of God.

00:06:18.912 --> 00:06:20.096
the love of God.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:30.048
Baptisms are one of my favorite things about Sunday morning services at our church. People tell their powerful stories of the things that God has done in their lives, and one of the things that we are over and over again

00:06:29.568 --> 00:06:39.616
and over and over again is this. I went through this difficult time and my group was there for me. So Community Group is an incredible opportunity for you to grow in your relationships with your

00:06:39.136 --> 00:06:49.184
Now just imagine what God might do in your group, in your church, maybe in your community, if you were to trust Him enough to allow Him

00:06:48.704 --> 00:06:58.752
him to grow you and change you through the relationships that you've begun to form. We hope you don't miss that opportunity and we hope you look back on this group and say it's one of the best decisions I've ever had.

00:06:58.272 --> 00:06:59.712
I ever made.

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:01.632
Thank you.

00:07:11.008 --> 00:07:20.896
We hope the past eight weeks have helped to set a foundation for a great group experience. We also hope that the relationships you've begun will grow you over time and move you to serve others.

00:07:20.672 --> 00:07:23.104
Next week, just enjoy hanging out.

00:07:22.912 --> 00:07:25.312
And also decide what study you'll do next.

00:07:24.928 --> 00:07:27.552
And when you begin that next study, remember,

00:07:27.424 --> 00:07:28.736
Keep showing up.

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:30.048
Keep joining in.

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:31.232
And keep being real.
